WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.880
Hi everyone, I'm Allison Horst. I'm an assistant teaching professor at the Bren School at UC

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:16.040
Santa Barbara, and over the past year I've also been RStudio's artist-in-residence. In

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:20.480
this talk I'm really excited to share with you some of the motivation behind my R artwork

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:26.400
and also some lessons I've learned from the R community along the way. To get started,

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:31.840
I want to ask you to think about what did it feel like for you the first time you started

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:39.119
learning R? Maybe you were one of the lucky ones where all you felt was happiness and

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:45.279
excitement and you knew this was going to be an awesome tool to learn, but for many

00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:51.279
people who are learning R or code for the first time, that's not the reaction. There

00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:58.279
can be some confusion at the idea of learning this new language. There can be some frustration.

00:00:58.279 --> 00:01:03.040
Maybe you were already happily working in another language and you're looking at R thinking

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:10.239
like, what is a kakapo? I want my pandas back. Maybe you were feeling frustrated as you tried

00:01:10.239 --> 00:01:15.599
to get up this steep learning curve. Or maybe you weren't even expecting to have to learn

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:20.360
how to code and you're looking at R just having a meltdown because it's something that's so

00:01:20.519 --> 00:01:26.519
completely new. And all of these feelings are pretty common for learners. And this isn't

00:01:26.519 --> 00:01:32.599
unique to R. A recent Google search for why is coding so dot dot dot reveals that a lot

00:01:32.599 --> 00:01:39.400
of the top searches related to why is coding so are not totally positive. Why is coding

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:45.400
so hard, so boring, complicated, frustrating, difficult, hard to learn, confusing, and stressful.

00:01:45.559 --> 00:01:50.919
And yes, mixed in here, there's some good ones like why is coding so important? And why is

00:01:50.919 --> 00:01:57.400
coding so fun? That might be an artifact of this being part of my search results. But the overall

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:03.160
takeaway is that for a lot of learners, R and learning to code in general can feel a little

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:10.119
bit intimidating and maybe not like a totally happy place. And not only can it feel a little

00:02:10.119 --> 00:02:16.600
bit intimidating, but it's also a big energy and time investment. There are so many things

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:21.960
to learn to get started in R and with coding in general. And there's always something new

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:27.399
coming out. For those of us who are happily working in R, maybe we are this green monster

00:02:27.399 --> 00:02:34.199
on the right where we see new tutorials and new resources or packages coming out every day.

00:02:34.199 --> 00:02:38.600
And we are so excited knowing that it can be something useful for us to learn and use.

00:02:39.479 --> 00:02:44.839
But we can imagine that for learners who are just trying to get up this steep learning curve,

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:49.639
seeing all of those new things coming out all the time could be a little bit daunting.

00:02:50.759 --> 00:02:57.399
So what can we do when something is hard to learn and we're asking a learner to make an investment?

00:02:58.199 --> 00:03:03.080
One thing that we can do is we can put in a little bit of extra work to help something that

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:10.520
originally doesn't look that appetizing feel a little bit more appetizing. For example,

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:15.240
if we know that vegetables contain a lot of really great nutrients, but it's hard to convince

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:20.759
somebody to eat them, maybe we can dress it up to look like a cute bug to make it more likely

00:03:20.759 --> 00:03:27.720
that they will invest in eating those vegetables. And people are already doing this in code. For

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:35.960
example, Julia Evans' zines that explain a lot of really important basics in CSS and Git and Bash

00:03:36.919 --> 00:03:42.919
are really useful teaching tools because they provide information for learners, but they also

00:03:42.919 --> 00:03:48.279
make it look very welcoming. These look like a thing that I would want to engage with.

00:03:49.479 --> 00:03:54.679
And I found myself wondering when I was teaching courses in R to graduate students,

00:03:54.679 --> 00:04:02.039
most of who never coded before, do those resources exist in R? Are there nice, welcoming,

00:04:02.839 --> 00:04:07.639
engaging illustrations that I could include in my course materials that would be a welcoming

00:04:07.639 --> 00:04:13.080
entryway for graduate students to learn new functions and packages? Because what I found

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:19.000
was that I would be up there in the front of a class so excited to introduce an amazing new

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.279
function. And on the screen behind me would be like a screenshot of the documentation,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.600
which contains a lot of really important information that's going to be essential

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:34.839
moving forward, but maybe was not the most inspiring first interaction that a student

00:04:34.839 --> 00:04:42.040
could have with a new function. Which made me think, yes, there is a place to create engaging

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:47.320
artwork that dresses up R a little bit to make it look more inviting and welcoming.

00:04:48.279 --> 00:04:54.440
And over the past year, that has been my entire goal as RStudio's artist-in-residence,

00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:59.720
has been to create useful and engaging illustrations that welcome users to explore,

00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:05.000
teach, and learn about new packages and functions in R. And they will still have to go on to eat

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:11.399
their vegetables and learn those hard skills, but the first interaction could be something that is

00:05:11.399 --> 00:05:18.119
fun and positive and welcoming. So for example, instead of their first view of Mutate being a

00:05:18.119 --> 00:05:24.920
screenshot of the documentation, maybe instead their first interaction with Mutate could be

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:31.079
seeing these helpful X-Men monsters adding a new column to an existing data frame. And over the

00:05:31.079 --> 00:05:37.160
past year, I've not only been creating many illustrations as a welcoming interaction with

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:42.760
different functions and packages in R, but I've also created illustrations showing general data

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:49.079
science principles and concepts, and also a whole bunch of hex stickers. But what I want to talk

00:05:49.079 --> 00:05:56.600
about now is what I've learned from the R community over the past year. And these have been really

00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:02.600
important lessons for me as an artist and as a data science teacher. And the first thing that

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:10.600
the R community has helped me to embrace is that cute and credible artwork coexist. Just like Bailey

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:15.320
the Golden Retriever is sitting here looking totally credible and professional while he develops

00:06:15.320 --> 00:06:24.519
his R package, he also is looking very adorable. And that can happen with artwork too. And even

00:06:24.519 --> 00:06:30.200
though I knew this, even though I knew that making and including artwork could be really useful for

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:35.799
effective communication, making slides more engaging, connecting to learners and clarifying

00:06:35.799 --> 00:06:42.119
concepts, showing empathy, lowering learning barriers, I just really love doing it. And also

00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:48.119
including artwork into course materials can really help students understand that yes, creativity and

00:06:48.119 --> 00:06:54.519
artwork have a place in science. Even though I knew those things, there was always this little

00:06:54.519 --> 00:07:00.440
gremlin on my shoulder saying, okay, you can lean hard into the artwork for R and data science

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:07.239
education, but just know that that might actually damage your credibility as a data scientist.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:14.359
And there was a turning point when I realized that this was totally unfounded. And that was

00:07:14.359 --> 00:07:21.000
when Hadley Wickham asked me to create a series of illustrations for an upcoming talk he was giving

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:26.519
called the Joy of Functional Programming. And I was so excited at this, I knew this was going to be

00:07:26.519 --> 00:07:33.000
like a big talk, a really awesome opportunity to share artwork. And I was expecting that because

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.440
this was a highly professional, important, advanced talk that that this was going to be

00:07:38.440 --> 00:07:44.920
maybe some sleek designs I was creating to go along with the slides. And to my absolute delight,

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:50.359
Hadley, when I asked him what style he was thinking about, responded that he was thinking

00:07:50.359 --> 00:07:56.119
about these monsters being included in this series. And I tried to play it cool and be like,

00:07:56.119 --> 00:08:01.079
oh yeah, of course the monsters would belong in there. But in my heart, I was just like, oh my

00:08:01.079 --> 00:08:09.000
gosh, the monsters have made it. And, and this is like cute artwork being invited to be at the top

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:15.000
level talks in R and data science. Not only were the monsters invited, but they were going to be

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:21.079
baking cupcakes in this series. So really capturing for me, this idea that cute and

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:26.679
credible are not at odds with each other, that including cute illustrations can be a really

00:08:26.679 --> 00:08:33.479
powerful teaching tool at any level. I think that one example that captures this so perfectly

00:08:33.479 --> 00:08:41.479
is the certified trainer badge from our studio, which is one adorable, but two is the badge that's

00:08:41.479 --> 00:08:47.320
used when the certified trainers get their certification, which are some of the top

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:54.840
educators in the R community. And this has been a theme that has been reinforced with pretty much

00:08:54.840 --> 00:09:01.719
every interaction I've had, both with our studio and in the R community is that there's a refreshing

00:09:01.719 --> 00:09:08.359
lack of ego about what educational materials look like. And everyone is always just welcoming and

00:09:08.359 --> 00:09:15.559
encouraging more approachable educational resources. What that means is that while I

00:09:15.559 --> 00:09:21.000
started with this little gremlin on my shoulder, questioning my credibility and bringing a lot of

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:28.200
doubt into my mind, what I have now is the same gremlin, which is now encouraging me and always

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:35.799
asking, can I actually make this more approachable or cuter somehow? The second big thing that I've

00:09:35.799 --> 00:09:41.479
learned from the R community over the past year is that art truly can be a useful teaching and

00:09:41.479 --> 00:09:47.559
learning tool that helps learners engage with and remember new functions. An example of the type of

00:09:47.559 --> 00:09:53.559
artwork I've been creating is this illustration for the string squish function. The job of string

00:09:53.559 --> 00:10:00.359
squish is to remove leading trailing and repeated interior white space from strings. And here we see

00:10:00.359 --> 00:10:06.200
these four monsters who are working together to squish this string and in doing so are ejecting

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:12.440
excess white space. This combination of having text and something verbally explained and also

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:17.159
an illustration showing what that function is doing, I think is a powerful combination that

00:10:17.159 --> 00:10:24.119
can help with retention. An example of this happening in the wild is this illustration

00:10:24.119 --> 00:10:31.400
that was trying to help people remember to use ungroup if they have used group by previously.

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:37.880
We have in the forefront two monsters who are at a birthday party and you can see that one of them

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:43.799
has received this amazing gift of group by. But more importantly for this illustration, we can

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:50.039
see in the background this other little monster holding ungroup as a gift who is just so hoping

00:10:50.039 --> 00:10:55.719
they're going to be included. And the reaction to this illustration was exactly what I was hoping

00:10:55.719 --> 00:11:01.799
it would be, which is an emotional reaction ensuring that people will not forget ungroup.

00:11:01.799 --> 00:11:07.880
For example, some of the responses were, I'm so sad for that little bub being left out. I'm always

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:13.320
going to remember this when using ungroup. I'm never going to look down on ungroup again. And my

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:19.239
favorite one is someone who said they were just able to help someone else solve a problem because

00:11:19.239 --> 00:11:25.000
they remembered this super cute and somewhat sad drawing. And I think this really reflects that

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:30.200
artwork can be a way to engage people's emotions that helps them remember important skills.

00:11:32.119 --> 00:11:39.159
Art can also be really useful in helping to clarify big or vague concepts. For example,

00:11:39.159 --> 00:11:47.640
I recently worked with Julia Lowndes on a series of illustrations to try to portray the benefits

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:54.599
of working with tidy data and organizing data in tidy data structure. And what this illustration

00:11:54.599 --> 00:12:01.159
is showing is that if you have datasets that are all in tidy structure, that you can use the same

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:09.719
tools in similar ways across datasets. But in contrast, if we have untidy data, what that means

00:12:09.719 --> 00:12:16.280
is we oftentimes are hacking together unique tools to deal with unique datasets in their own unique

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:22.359
ways, which is challenging and tedious and makes it hard to collaborate with people. So I think that

00:12:22.359 --> 00:12:27.799
this series was really useful in taking some kind of big picture ideas about the benefits of tidy

00:12:27.799 --> 00:12:36.760
data and capturing them in a way that is more memorable visually. Artwork can also make things

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:41.719
that are kind of intimidating for learners feel a little bit more friendly and provide a more

00:12:41.719 --> 00:12:49.000
welcoming entryway. For example, for loops usually aren't the thing that learners are the most excited

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:55.400
to learn, but they're especially intimidating when it's just like sequences of numbers and the code

00:12:55.400 --> 00:13:02.359
coming in and out that's a little bit daunting to look at. So what if instead there could be a vector

00:13:02.359 --> 00:13:08.599
that's actually a parade of monsters? And in going through that for loop, depending on the shape of

00:13:08.599 --> 00:13:14.280
the monster, they are either assigned to get sunglasses or a hat. And then what we can see is

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:20.039
the outcome is the result of each of those monsters going through that for loop and either getting

00:13:20.039 --> 00:13:26.520
their sunglasses or hat. And the third thing that I've learned is that art can be an incredibly

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:33.719
powerful tool for creating supportive communities. As a landscape painter originally, I did not

00:13:33.719 --> 00:13:40.760
understand how important this could be, but art can be a way to directly show support for learners.

00:13:42.280 --> 00:13:48.359
It can show empathy. For example, here we see this little bud who is just needing to take a minute,

00:13:48.359 --> 00:13:53.799
so it can be really useful for showing empathy when learners are maybe struggling or feeling alone

00:13:53.799 --> 00:14:00.520
in the struggles that they're facing. It can be a way to engage the community by creating activities

00:14:00.520 --> 00:14:06.280
that include artwork. For example, with these coloring book illustrations of Our Session Aborted

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:14.039
and everyone's favorite Objective Type Closure is Not Subsettable. And it can also just be a really

00:14:14.039 --> 00:14:19.080
cool way that different groups and communities can represent themselves and make other people

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:25.239
feel included. The most common way that we see this is in the many hex stickers that exist

00:14:25.239 --> 00:14:30.520
that different groups, organizations, and even packages are used to represent themselves.

00:14:32.599 --> 00:14:39.479
And I had no idea before joining the art community the power that a 2 inch by 1.73 inch

00:14:39.479 --> 00:14:47.479
hexagonal design could have. And this is something that I was so amazed by is the support and demand

00:14:47.479 --> 00:14:54.039
for hex stickers that I think really reflects how excited people are to have something that they can

00:14:54.119 --> 00:14:58.679
put on their computer or whatever to represent themselves in the groups that they're a part of.

00:15:00.919 --> 00:15:06.520
So in summary, what I've learned over the past year and that has been reinforced by so many people

00:15:06.520 --> 00:15:13.239
in the R community is that creative contributions can make coding and R a more welcoming or even

00:15:13.239 --> 00:15:20.359
just a more fun place for learners and users at all levels. And knowing that, what can we do

00:15:20.359 --> 00:15:28.440
to create and support more art in R? And the first thing is we can find ways to support creative

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:34.919
contributions. So at whatever level makes sense for you, how can you support artists and creative

00:15:34.919 --> 00:15:41.080
contributors? Just by watching this talk, you are supporting creative contributions. But you can

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:46.599
also include artwork in your teaching resources. You can like or share artwork that's posted on

00:15:46.599 --> 00:15:51.880
Twitter. Whatever level makes sense for you, I guarantee that your support will be meaningful

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:57.479
for an artist and will make them want to create more. The second is you could think about ways

00:15:57.479 --> 00:16:02.679
to more formally collaborate with creative contributors. For example, can you contract

00:16:02.679 --> 00:16:08.599
an artist to add something to your resources? Can you write an artist into a grant that you're

00:16:08.599 --> 00:16:13.960
working on? Or can you create an artist in residence program where I guarantee you will

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:19.239
have your work reflected in a way that's really engaging for people who might not have otherwise

00:16:19.239 --> 00:16:25.719
known about or engaged with it? And finally, I would ask you to think about ways that you can be

00:16:25.719 --> 00:16:31.559
a creative contributor. So what do you do that you might be able to share with the community?

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:38.760
We already have this amazing community of people and so many of them are creating and sharing

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:47.559
incredible artwork and fabric and are generated designs, 3D renderings, amazing graphic designs

00:16:47.559 --> 00:16:54.119
made in ggplot and so many other things. And we should think about what other types of artwork or

00:16:54.119 --> 00:17:00.520
creative contributions would we want to invite? And the answer should be all of them. Baking,

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:06.920
music and sculpture, dance. There is someone in the world who can do the perfect interpretive

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:14.199
dance of pivot longer and pivot wider and I want to experience that. Memes, design, poetry, art and

00:17:14.199 --> 00:17:21.560
activities and so much more so that we can be creating artwork and creative contributions

00:17:21.560 --> 00:17:26.839
that engage and resonate with every different R user who we would want to feel included.

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:32.359
And sometimes I think there's this pressure if you're thinking about what can I contribute,

00:17:32.359 --> 00:17:37.880
there can sometimes be pressure to like feel like there has to be some learning outcome or

00:17:37.880 --> 00:17:44.119
somebody has to have a takeaway or a new skill. And I encourage you to remember that making someone

00:17:44.119 --> 00:17:49.959
feel a little bit happier while they're trying to learn something hard is an absolutely great reason

00:17:49.959 --> 00:17:55.959
to create and share your art. One experience that I had with this recently was I was having kind of

00:17:55.959 --> 00:18:02.439
a rough day, I was mope scrolling through Twitter and I happened to come across Jacqueline Nollis's

00:18:02.439 --> 00:18:08.520
picture of the R pancakes that she had created. And this didn't solve my coding problems, this

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:15.000
didn't write my lecture for me, but what it did do is it made me exclaim, R pancakes! And then I

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:20.199
just continued on my day a little bit happier because R pancakes had existed in the world.

00:18:20.439 --> 00:18:27.640
So to wrap up, no, art is not the solution to tech's problems, especially related to

00:18:27.640 --> 00:18:34.359
inclusion and welcoming. Unless we're talking about this whale tail sculpture that is literally

00:18:34.359 --> 00:18:39.719
saving a train that's gone off the end of the tracks, art is not going to save tech, which is

00:18:39.719 --> 00:18:45.640
why I'm so grateful for the many organizations, groups, individuals, and initiatives, just some

00:18:45.719 --> 00:18:50.599
of which are shown here, that have been doing this hard work to make R more welcoming for more

00:18:50.599 --> 00:18:57.959
users since before I even started using R. So while R is not the solution, I hope that it can

00:18:57.959 --> 00:19:05.000
be a supporting piece that helps those efforts by making the entire landscape of R, which is already

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:10.920
so vibrant, even a little bit sunnier. I look forward to talking with many of you about all

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:17.239
the different ways we can contribute more creative things to the R community. Thank you.

